Figure 2a represents the arrangement of the pharmacophoric features along with their inter-feature distance constraints. Figure 2b, c shows the mapping of the most (P1) and the least active (P25) compounds of the training set on Model 1, respectively. The hydroxyl group in the hydroxamic acid of P1 mapped upon the A feature, while the secondary amino (protonated) and the phenyl group of P1  mapped over P and RA features, respectively. The phenyl and carbonyl groups of the compound P25 mapped upon the RA and A features, respectively. The fit values of P1 and P25 were 5.61 and 1.95, respectively. It is observed that most of the highly active compounds in the training set contained positive ionizable primary amine group. Although some active (e.g. P5, of fit value 4.47) and moderately active (e.g., P8, fit value 4.29) compounds lacked this feature, showed considerable APN inhibitory activity. These compounds contained amide group that mapped over the donor feature. Therefore, it may be assumed that some polar groups, in addition to positively charged groups, also determine higher binding potential of these ligands.


